metadata.name: Miniscapes #377
metadata.description:
Miniscapes merges generative code (Rich's bit) with meticulously designed scenes and elements (Rick's bit), to create minimalist landscapes intended to charm, delight, and surprise.

Our aim was to convey as much as possible with as little as possible by using simple shapes and lines to represent a wide variety of natural landscapes.

We hope that you find as much joy in owning a Miniscape as we did in creating them.

Controls (in live view):
- Press [s] to save the current image
- Press [p] to pause an animated output
- Press [r] to reset an animated output (this will also pause)

metadata.name: In a Moment, a Thousand Years #101
metadata.description:
Fragmented time and fractured memories.

=========

Controls:

[1] set resolution to 716 x 1024px (default)
[2] set resolution to 1433 x 2048px
[3] set resolution to 2455 x 3508px (approx. the size of A4 paper)
[4] set resolution to 3472 x 4961px (approx. the size of A3 paper)
[5] set resolution to 4911 x 7016px (approx. the size of A2 paper)

[0] set resolution to current window size

[c] capture a screenshot at rendered resolution

*The higher resolution settings (3-5) can slow down your device, especially on a low-end laptop without a dedicated GPU. Use it only to render and download a hi-res output for printing. For screen viewing [1] or [2] is recommended.



Made with cables.gl, a node-based webgl environment

XALTED 2022

metadata.name: Trasiedoc #475
metadata.description:
Behind every generative art project is a code. This code is sometimes a masterpiece but most viewers do not see it.

With the Trasiedoc project I wanted to highlight the hidden face of generative art, the code, by literally integrating the code of my biggest project to date (Dencity) in each output of the Trasiedoc project.

Margins can be hidden by pressing "x" in live mode (and optionally press "p" to see if anything happens).

Made with ‚ù§Ô∏è, code, code and p5js.

metadata.name: Loomnatic #53
metadata.description:
"Loomnatic" is a lunatic loom who loves to weave. It sometimes generates fabrics you can see in real life. However, most of the time, its outputs would look extraordinary.

How the loom "weaves" a fabric:
- Create a vector field for the warp threads with the improved Perlin noise developed by Ken Perlin.
- Derive a new vector field from the old one for the weft threads by rotating its angles.
- Calculate the curve vertices with an algorithm developed by Bruno Jobard and Wilfrid Lefer that creates evenly-spaced streamlines of arbitrary density.
- Interpolate each set of curve vertices to form a Catmull-Rom spline and then convert it to a thread polygon with varying thread weights.
- Calculate the intersection polygons of all pairs of interweaving threads with math and geometry.
- Use the intersection polygons to create the textile effect during the drawing stage.

Every token can output in 13 different aspect ratios:
1x1, 3x1, 1x3, 3x2, 2x3, 4x3, 3x4, 5x4, 4x5, 16x9, 9x16, 16x10, 10x16

And downloadable in 4 different resolutions:
1. 1000px
2. 2000px
3. 4000px
4. 8000px

Click on the image in live view to unlock all these possibilities.

Created with Vanilla JavaScript.
